  "faqs": [
    {
      "q": "How long does a stepparent adoption take in Tennessee?",
      "a": "Most uncontested stepparent adoptions in Tennessee take between 3 and 6 months from filing to finalization. The timeline depends on court availability, whether the other parent's rights need to be terminated, and how quickly the required documents are gathered."
    },
    {
      "q": "Do I need a home study for a stepparent adoption?",
      "a": "Not always. Tennessee law allows the court to waive the home study requirement in stepparent adoptions when the petitioner has lived with the child for a sufficient period and the circumstances warrant it. We'll advise you based on your specific situation."
    },
    {
      "q": "What if the birth parent won't consent to adoption?",
      "a": "If a birth parent refuses to consent, the court can still terminate their parental rights in certain circumstances — such as abandonment, failure to pay support, or unfitness. These are contested adoptions, which require a court hearing. We have extensive experience in contested adoption cases."
    },
    {
      "q": "How much does adoption cost in Tennessee?",
      "a": "Costs vary significantly by adoption type. Stepparent and relative adoptions are typically the most affordable ($1,500–$4,000 in attorney fees). Private placement adoptions may involve additional costs including birth parent expenses, agency fees, and court costs. We provide transparent fee estimates in your consultation."
    },
    {
      "q": "Can same-sex couples adopt in Tennessee?",
      "a": "Yes. Tennessee recognizes the right of same-sex couples to adopt. We proudly serve LGBTQ+ families in all types of adoption, including stepparent, second-parent, and agency adoptions."
    },
    {
      "q": "What is the Interstate Compact on the Placement of Children (ICPC)?",
      "a": "The ICPC is a legal agreement between all U.S. states that governs how children can be placed for adoption across state lines. Before a child placed for adoption in one state can be brought to another state, both states must approve the placement. This adds time and paperwork — but we handle all of it."
    },
    {
      "q": "Do I need an attorney for adoption in Tennessee?",
      "a": "Yes. Tennessee law requires that all adoptions be finalized in court, and you must have a licensed Tennessee attorney represent you. Attempting to complete an adoption without an attorney significantly increases the risk of errors that can delay or derail the process."
    },
    {
      "q": "What rights does an adopted child have?",
      "a": "An adopted child has the same legal rights as a biological child — including inheritance rights, the right to be covered by a parent's insurance, and access to Social Security benefits. The child will receive a new birth certificate listing the adoptive parent(s)."
    }
  ],
